  "prompt": "What were the major events of Spain in 1492?",
  "response": "The year 1492 was a pivotal year in Spanish history, marked by several significant events:\n\n1. **The Reconquista**: The completion of the Reconquista occurred on January 2, 1492, when the Catholic Monarchs, Ferdinand II of Aragon and Isabella I of Castile, captured Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in Spain. This event marked the end of nearly 800 years of Muslim rule in parts of the Iberian Peninsula.\n\n2. **The Alhambra Decree**: Shortly after the fall of Granada, on March 31, 1492, the Catholic Monarchs issued the Alhambra Decree, which ordered the expulsion of Jews from Spain who refused to convert to Christianity. This decree led to the forced exodus of a large portion of the Jewish population, profoundly affecting Spanish society and culture.\n\n3. **Christopher Columbus' Voyage**: In August 1492, Christopher Columbus, funded by Ferdinand and Isabella, set sail from Spain on his expedition to find a westward route to Asia. On October 12, 1492, he reached what is now known as the Bahamas, making contact with the Americas and marking the beginning of European exploration and colonization of the New World.\n\nThese events collectively transformed Spain politically, culturally, and economically, setting the stage for its emergence as a leading global power in the following centuries.",
